In programming, the keyword `static` is used to declare variables, methods, or classes that have a specific behavior.

**Static Variables**

When a variable is declared as `static`, it means that it is shared by all instances of a class. In other words, there is only one copy of the variable, and it is not unique to each instance of the class.

Here's an example:
```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int myVariable = 10;
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyClass obj1 = new MyClass();
        MyClass obj2 = new MyClass();
        System.out.println(obj1.myVariable); // prints 10
        System.out.println(obj2.myVariable); // prints 10
        obj1.myVariable = 20;
        System.out.println(obj2.myVariable); // still prints 10
    }
}
```
In this example, `myVariable` is a `static` variable, so both `obj1` and `obj2` are referencing the same variable.

